      "rationale": "The FEA models employ a direct sparse linear solver (MKL PARDISO / Ansys sparse direct) for a static implicit analysis with no time-stepping or iterative convergence loops. Numerical solver error in the ASME V&V 40 sense (iterative solver residual, time-integration truncation error) is not applicable because the solution is obtained via exact LU factorisation to machine precision. No iterative tolerance or time-step sensitivity study is required or meaningful for this problem class."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error addresses variability introduced by different analysts applying the same modeling protocol with different choices. In this study, all three modelling teams (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) followed a single pre-specified simulation protocol with locked boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions documented in a shared analysis plan. Inter-analyst variability was explicitly captured as part of the model-form uncertainty budget rather than as a separate use-error factor, making a standalone use-error assessment redundant and not applicable."
    },
    {
